TY  - JOUR
T1  - Firm–Stakeholder Dialogue and the Media: The Evolution of Stakeholder Evaluations in Different Informational Environments
AU  - Dorobantu, Sinziana
AU  - Henisz, Witold J.
AU  - Nartey, Lite J.
Y1  - 2023/03/27
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2024/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2021.0103
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2021.0103
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 92
EP  - 125
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We propose that the informational environment in which firm?stakeholder interactions are embedded shapes the effect of firm?stakeholder dialogue on a stakeholder?s evaluation of a firm. How much stakeholders know about a firm (information availability), what stakeholders know about a firm (information content), and how much they trust the media that informs them (information reliability) vary across countries, firms, and time. We theorize and assess how these three dimensions of the informational environment shape the effects of firm?stakeholder dialogue on the evolution of a stakeholder?s evaluation of a firm. We illustrate our arguments with insights from field interviews conducted to understand stakeholders? evaluations of the Rosia Montana gold mine in Romania, and we analyze them using original, manually coded stakeholder-level data that capture 2,454 stakeholders? evaluations of 26 gold-mining operations around the world.
AB  - We propose that the informational environment in which firm?stakeholder interactions are embedded shapes the effect of firm?stakeholder dialogue on a stakeholder?s evaluation of a firm. How much stakeholders know about a firm (information availability), what stakeholders know about a firm (information content), and how much they trust the media that informs them (information reliability) vary across countries, firms, and time. We theorize and assess how these three dimensions of the informational environment shape the effects of firm?stakeholder dialogue on the evolution of a stakeholder?s evaluation of a firm. We illustrate our arguments with insights from field interviews conducted to understand stakeholders? evaluations of the Rosia Montana gold mine in Romania, and we analyze them using original, manually coded stakeholder-level data that capture 2,454 stakeholders? evaluations of 26 gold-mining operations around the world.
